  <bioghist id="aspace_5550bb108fd9513cea03f338ee583186">
    <head>Biographical Note</head>
<p>Adam Purple (born David Lloyd Wilkie, 1930-2015) was an author, activist, "guerrilla gardener," and a participant in the urban gardening movement that occurred in New York City's Lower East Side during the 1970s and 1980s. His most notable work was an open community garden located on Forsyth Street called the Garden of Eden. </p><p>Adam Purple was born in Independence, Missouri, in 1930 and attended college in Kansas. He later served in the United States Army, and worked as a teacher and journalist. In 1964, Purple emigrated to Sydney, Australia, with his family and worked as a literature and English teacher. Adam Purple was convicted in Australia of sexually abusing his stepdaughter and was subsequently deported. Once back in the United States, he moved to the Haight-Ashbury neighborhood of San Francisco before settling in New York City's Lower East Side in 1968. Adam Purple died from a heart attack while bicycling across the Williamsburg Bridge on September 14, 2015. After his death, additional allegations of abuse were made by family members.</p><p>Sources:</p><p>Lincoln Anderson, "All Purple's Daughters," amNewYork, January 21, 2016. https://www.amny.com/news/all-purples-daughters/. </p><p>Lincoln Anderson, "The Dark Side of Adam Purple," <emph render="italic">The Villager</emph> (New York, NY), December 31, 2015.</p>  </bioghist>
  <scopecontent id="aspace_c4f411844bd8b407755342e60f6dbe3f">
    <head>Scope and Contents</head>
<p>The Harvey Wang Collection on Adam Purple documents the work of author, activist, and "guerrilla gardener" Adam Purple. Wang first met Purple in 1977 and went on to document Purple's career in New York City until his death in 2015. Wang featured Adam Purple and his work in his 1990 book <emph render="italic">New York</emph>. David Isay, who later founded the oral history non-profit StoryCorps, co-authored this book with Wang. This collection is comprised of photographs taken by Wang, as well as material Wang collected that relates to Purple's time in New York City, specifically his gardens and his written works.</p><p>Photographs in this collection, which include digital photographs, printed photographs, and slides, depict Adam Purple's Garden of Eden and document its creation, as well as what remains today and how it has been incorporated into the low-income housing development that replaced it. The collection also includes correspondence and petitions opposing the destruction of the Garden of Eden; posters promoting Purple's writings like <emph render="italic">Zentences!</emph>; flyers raising awareness of the Garden of Eden's upcoming demolition; copies of his written serials including "Inner City Lights," "Busimess," "People's Telephone," and "Life with les(s) Ego"; and news clippings related to Adam Purple and his gardens.</p><p>In 2006, Amy Brost interviewed Adam Purple for StoryCorps, and in 2011 she and Wang used the interview as a basis for the short film <emph render="italic">Adam Purple and the Garden of Eden</emph>. In his interview with StoryCorps, Purple briefly discusses his early life, his experiences living in the Lower East Side, and his concerns about the environment and climate change. He also provides detail about what inspired him to create the Garden of Eden, how he constructed the garden, the types of produce he planted, his long-term goals for the garden, and the disappointment he felt when the city destroyed it in 1986. A copy of this interview recording and transcript can be found within the collection. </p>  </scopecontent>
